@node Intro "MailBox : Introduction"
                           @{b}Introduction to MailBox@{ub}

Mailbox is an ARexx module for Directory Opus  5.5  which  creates  a  MailBox
AppIcon  on  your  DOpus5  screen.  You  can specify different icons for empty
mailbox, old and new mail. The icon text gives information about the  size  of
the  mailbox  or  number of new emails, and more details are available via the
pop-ip menu. You can also define actions for  the  arrival  of  new  mail  and
double-clicking of or dropping files on the icon.

@{b}Advantages@{ub}

 * Displays plenty of information about your mailbox either in the  icon  text
   or via a requester.
 * Because it's simply a matter of editing the script, the actions (and indeed
   all other aspects of the program) are  highly  configurable  and  flexible,
   although you will need some knowledge of ARexx to get the best from it.

@{b}Disadvantages@{ub}

 * Relies on your local mail delivery system sending a message to some message
   port every time a new email is recieved.
 * Does not automatically notice changes in mailbox size.
@endnode

@node Usage "MailBox : Usage"
                                @{b}Using MailBox@{ub}

To install MailBox, simply copy the supplied icons  to  DOpus5:Icons  and  the
script to DOpus5:Modules. This should immediately pop up an AppIcon displaying
an empty mailbox and install an internal Opus  command  which  allows  you  to
control  the program. To get it to do anything useful, you'll now need to edit
the @{"configuration" link Config} within the script.

@{b}MailBox Close/S@{ub}

This internal Opus command has three possible actions:

 * Open the MailBox appicon if it is not already open.
 * Refresh the mailbox size if the icon is open.
 * If the Close switch is supplied, close an open appicon.

@{b}Mouse Actions@{ub}

Double-clicking on the MailBox appicon will refresh  it,  including  resetting
the count of new emails recieved to 0. You can also define other actions (such
as loading your mailer) to be carried out by editing the script appropriately.
You  can also define actions to be carried out when files are dropped onto the
appicon.

@{b}Pop-up Menu@{ub}

@{i}Close         @{ui}  Remove the MailBox appicon.
@{i}Information...@{ui}  Pop up a requester with more information about your mailbox.

@{i}Snapshot      @{ui}  Snapshot the appicon's position and lock state.
@{i}Un-Snapshot   @{ui}  Removes the snapshot information.

@{i}Lock          @{ui}  Lock the appicon so that it cannot be moved.
@{i}Un-Lock       @{ui}  Allow the icon to be moved again.

@{i}Refresh       @{ui}  Refresh the mailbox size information.
@{i}Mailer...     @{ui}  Perform the same action as a double-click.

@endnode

@node Config "MailBox : Configuration"
                             @{b}Configuring MailBox@{ub}

The basic configuration of MailBox is done by editing the four sections of the
ARexx  script  which  are  contained  with in pairs of long comment lines. The
first of these sets up the locations of various files,  the  message  port  to
monitor and some startup defaults. The other three sections are used to define
the actions to be carried out on various events.

@{b}Settings@{ub}

@{i}MailFile @{ui}  This should be set to the location of your  mailbox  to  which  new
            mail is appended, for example HOME:Mail/<username>

@{i}EmptyIcon@{ui}  This is the image to be used when your mailbox is empty (ie  0K  in
            size or non-existant) The  .info  suffix  should  @{b}not@{ub}  be
            given.
@{i}OldIcon  @{ui}  This is the image to be used if your mailbox is non-empty, but  you
            have no new mail. The .info suffix should @{b}not@{ub} be given.
@{i}NewIcon  @{ui}  This is the image to be used if you do have  new  mail.  The  .info
            suffix should @{b}not@{ub} be given.

@{i}MailPort @{ui}  This is the name of the message port to be monitored  for  messages
            notifying the arrival of new email. The  default  is  'T:MailRdy',
            which works with SMTPd/SMTPPost from INetUtils on AmiNet, and  may
            work with other systems.

@{i}SnapFile @{ui}  This is the file in which MailBox stores its snapshot data.

@{i}Startup  @{ui}  Set this to 'yes' if you want MailBox to open it's icon  when  Opus
            is started, or 'no' if you do not.
@{i}ILock    @{ui}  Set this to 1 if you want the MailBox icon to be locked  (immobile)
            initially, or 0 if you do not.  This  will  be  overidden  by  any
            previous snapshot.

@{b}New Mail@{ub}

In this block you can define code  which  will  be  executed  every  time  you
recieve  a  new  piece of email (ie a message is recieved @{b}and@{ub} the size of your
mailbox file has increased). For example, you can make Opus play an apropriate
sampled sound.

@{b}Go To Mailer@{ub}

This block of code will be executed whenever you double-click on  the  appicon
or  select  the  'Mailer...'  item from the pop-up menu. The intention is that
this should be used to load or bring to the front your email program.

@{b}Files Dropped on AppIcon@{ub}

Here you can set up code do be run when a file or files  are  dropped  on  The
MailBox  appicon.  This  could  then  tell  your mail program to open these as
mailboxes or add them as includes to the email currently  being  composed,  or
maybe even both.
@endnode

